Running a business as a creative introvert on your own and being extremely private shouldn't be complicated, yet it often is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with the big (and diabolical) tech companies using extravert techniques. Here, do some advertising, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service verified, be available 24/7, respond to questions with a video of yourself, respond right away. Video, video, video.
January 3, 2024.
It's a year of transition for me.
I don't want to feed the big tech companies with my money, my data, and my energy. Nor do I want coaches who have only one extravert solution that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my activity while fighting against the idea I've long believed, that one has to do things a certain way to succeed.
Good luck to me!
I've already taken the first steps.
I've left Facebook, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I've removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to a European-based CRM for better GDPR compliance, and I will be transferring my activity over the next few weeks.
I've transferred my MX to Proton and I'm now fully benefiting from SPF, DKIM and DMARC, without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
03/03/2024
